Spiny Lobster Abundance in California

Janelle Christensen & Lauren Manzo

11/11/2019

Introduction

The California Spiny Lobster (panulirus interruptus) is an important species in the kelp forests in California. Lobsters are a vital predator of kelp-eating sea urchins. Without predation, sea urchins have the ability to demolish kelp forests and create urchin barrens, destroying the ecological diversity that kelp forests create.

Figure 1. The Santa Barbara Chanel Long Term Ecological Research (SBC LTER) Credit: SBC LTER

Figure 2. California Spiny Lobster Credit: Catalina Island Marine Institute

Data and Methods

Data for this project was collected from 2012-2018 by the Santa Barbara Chanel Long Term Ecological Research team. Lobster numbers and sizes were collected by divers at 5 sites, including two Marine Protected Areas (Naples and Isla Vista) and three (Arroyo Quemado, Mohawk and Carpinteria). All samples were gathered in the late summer before the start of the fishing season.

Naples and Isla Vista were designated Marine Protected Areas in January 2012.

Results

1. Observed annual lobster abundance at the five sites over time

In the two marine protected areas, lobster numbers increased by 1212 lobsters (increasing by an average of 242.4 lobsters per year). While lobsters in the three Non-Marine Protected Areas increased by only 362 lobsters (increasing by an average of 72.4 lobsters per year).

Figure 3: Annual lobster abundance observed from 2012 - 2018 in five sites that were either Marine Protected or Non-Marine Protected areas in the Santa Barbara Channel. Marine Protected Areas showed change in lobster abundance over the sampling period.

Results

2. Lobster size distribution shifts in each site between the years 2012 and 2018

Lobster sizes in the three Non-Marine Protected Areas were observed to have less than noticeable shifts in lobster sizes whereas lobsters. While lobster sizes in Marine Protected Areas did have noticeable shifts.

Figure 4: Lobster sizes observed from 2012 and 2018 in five sites that were either Marine Protected or Non-Marine Protected areas in the Santa Barbara Channel. Marine Protected Areas showed change in lobster size over the sampling period.

3. Mean lobster sizes at Marine Protected Areas vs. Non-Marine Protected Areas

Figure 5: Mean lobster size increased significantly overall in Marine Protected Areas with the mean lobster size did not significantly increase in Non-Marine Protected Areas

Results

For the two Marine protected areas, comparing the means between 2012 and 2018 (n = 1276), the mean for 2012 is 67.38 \(\pm\) 12.15, and the mean for 2018 is 77.57 \(\pm\) 11.7 with an actual difference in mean size between the two years being 10.19 (two-sided t-test, t(32.5) = -4.69, p = 0)

For the three Non-Marine Protected Areas, comparing the means between 2012 and 2018, the mean for 2012 is 74.92 \(\pm\) 12.41, the mean for 2018 is 73.6199644 \(\pm\) 12.41 with an actual difference in mean size between the two years being -1.3 (two-sited t-test, t(296.01) = 1.33, p = 0.18)

For 2012, between Marine Protected Areas and Non-Marine Protected Areas, with an actual difference in mean size between the two areas being 7.55 (two-sided t-test, t(42.09) = -3.25, p = 0.0023)

For 2018, between Marine Protected Areas and Non-Marine Protected Areas, with an actual difference in mean size between the two areas being 3.95 (two - sided t-test t(1239.51) = 7.31, p = 0)
